1":"1231","1121":"1121","1153":"1153","1251":"1251","1152":"1152","1184":"1184","1194":"1194","1161":"1161","1171":"1171","1206":"1206","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","1189":"1189","1188":"1188","1209":"1209","Tours-en-Vimeu, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Tours-en-Vimeu, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Gamaches, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Gamaches, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gamaches","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Normand, Adrien, Lucien, Marcel, Aime, Andre, Camille, Fernand, Pierre, Raoul, Aldege.","French: habitational name from (La) Gamache or Gamaches, the name of several places in various parts of France, e.g. in Somme, possibly named from the Celtic elements <i>cam</i> ‘bent, winding’ + <i>apia</i> ‘water’.","History: Nicolas Gamache from Saint-Illiers-la-Ville in Yvelines, France, married Élisabeth-Ursule Cloutier in Château-Richer, QC, in 1676."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Elisabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."],"variants":[{"name":"Elizabeth","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Elisabeth de Gamaches was born in 1171, in Gamaches, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, her father, Alphonse De Gamache, was 50 and her mother, Hildegarde De Creseque, was 36. She married Jean 1er DE QUIERET-DE NOUVION in 1188. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1231, in Tours-en-Vimeu, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1171–1231":"1171–1231","1152–1209":"1152–1209","1153–1206":"1153–1206","1161–1224":"1161–1224","–Male":"Surnud","1194–1251":"1194–1251","1121–1184":"1121–1184","1135–1189":"1135–1189","1231":"1231","1121":"1121","1153":"1153","1251":"1251","1152":"1152","1184":"1184","1194":"1194","1161":"1161","1171":"1171","1206":"1206","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","1189":"1189","1188":"1188","1209":"1209","Tours-en-Vimeu, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Tours-en-Vimeu, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Gamaches, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Gamaches, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1171–1231":"1171–1231","1152–1209":"1152–1209","1153–1206":"1153